1ï¸âƒ£ Importing Stuff (The Tools We Need)

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from "react";
import "./App.css";
```
These are like bringing tools before building something.
- `React` â†’ The main library that lets us build web apps using components.
- `useState` â†’ A special tool (called a Hook) that lets us store data that can change, like the list of todos or what the user typed.
- `useEffect` â†’ Another Hook that lets us run code when something changes, like saving data.
- `"./App.css"` â†’ The file that has all our styles (colors, buttons, layout).

2ï¸âƒ£ The Big Box (Our App Component)

```jsx
export default function App() {
```
Think of this as the main box where everything lives. This is our â€œAppâ€ â€” the main house ğŸ  where all the code for our todo list stays.
`export default` just means we can easily use it in other files later.

3ï¸âƒ£ Keeping Track of What User Types

```jsx
const [newItem, setNewItem] = useState("");
```
This is like having a notebook ğŸ“ to remember what the user types.
- `newItem` â†’ the text in the input box.
- `setNewItem` â†’ a helper to update that text.

4ï¸âƒ£ Keeping Track of All Todos

```jsx
const [todos, setTodos] = useState(() => {
  const localValue = localStorage.getItem("ITEMS");
  return localValue ? JSON.parse(localValue) : [];
});
```
This is our todo list memory ğŸ§ .
- We try to grab saved todos from `localStorage` (a small storage in the browser).
- If we find some â†’ we load them.
- If not â†’ we start with an empty list.

5ï¸âƒ£ Saving Todos Automatically

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  localStorage.setItem("ITEMS", JSON.stringify(todos));
}, [todos]);
```
Whenever `todos` changes (like adding or deleting a task), this code saves it in the browser.
So even if you close or refresh the page, your list stays there! ğŸª„

6ï¸âƒ£ Adding a New Todo

```jsx
function handleSubmit(e) {
  e.preventDefault();
  if (newItem.trim() === "") return;
  setTodos(currentTodos => [
    ...currentTodos,
    { id: crypto.randomUUID(), title: newItem, completed: false }
  ]);
  setNewItem("");
}
```
What this does:
- Stops the form from refreshing.
- Checks if the input box is empty â€” if yes, it does nothing.
- Creates a new todo item (with a unique ID).
- Adds it to the list.
- Clears the input box.

7ï¸âƒ£ Marking a Todo as Done âœ…

```jsx
function toggleTodo(id, completed) {
  setTodos(currentTodos =>
    currentTodos.map(todo =>
      todo.id === id ? { ...todo, completed } : todo
    )
  );
}
```
This finds the todo with the given ID and changes its `completed` status.  
If you check the box, itâ€™s done. If you uncheck it, itâ€™s undone.

8ï¸âƒ£ Deleting a Todo âŒ

```jsx
function deleteTodo(id) {
  setTodos(currentTodos =>
    currentTodos.filter(todo => todo.id !== id)
  );
}
```
This simply removes a todo by keeping only those whose ID is not equal to the one clicked.

9ï¸âƒ£ The HTML-Like Part (JSX)

```jsx
return (
  <>
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit} className="new-item-form">
      <div>
        <label htmlFor="item">New Item</label>
        <input
          value={newItem}
          onChange={e => setNewItem(e.target.value)}
          type="text"
          id="item"
        />
      </div>
      <button className="btn" type="submit">Add</button>
    </form>
```
This is the part that shows up on screen.
- The form listens for a submit (Enter or Add button).
- Input box shows what the user types and updates `newItem`.
- Button adds the todo when clicked.

ğŸ”Ÿ Displaying the Todo List

```jsx
<ul className="list">
  {todos.length === 0 && "No Todos"}
  {todos.map(todo => (
    <li key={todo.id}>
      <label>
        <input
          type="checkbox"
          checked={todo.completed}
          onChange={e => toggleTodo(todo.id, e.target.checked)}
        />
        {todo.title}
      </label>
      <button onClick={() => deleteTodo(todo.id)} className="btn btn-danger">
        Delete
      </button>
    </li>
  ))}
</ul>
```
- If there are no todos, it says â€œNo Todosâ€.
- Otherwise, it loops through each todo and shows it.
- Checkbox toggles done/undone.
- Delete button removes it.

ğŸ¯ How Everything Works Together

1. You type something â†’ it goes into `newItem`.
2. You press Add â†’ `handleSubmit` creates a todo and adds it to `todos`.
3. React re-renders â†’ the new todo shows up.
4. You check/uncheck â†’ `toggleTodo` updates its state.
5. You delete â†’ `deleteTodo` removes it.
6. Every change gets saved into localStorage via `useEffect`.
7. Refresh â†’ the todos come right back!

Everything connects like a team â€” input, state, and UI all work together to make this app interactive and smart! ğŸ§ âœ¨

